          </setup>
          <statement>
            <p><m>f(x) = 1/(1-x)</m> (show equality only on <m>(-1,0)</m>)</p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>Given a value <m>x</m>, the magnitude of the error term <m>R_n(x)</m> is bounded by
              <me>
                \abs{R_n(x)} \leq \frac{\max\abs{\,f^{(n+1)}(z)}}{(n+1)!}\abs{x^{(n+1)}},
              </me>
              where <m>z</m> is between <m>0</m> and <m>x</m>.</p>

            <p>Note that <m>\abs{f^{(n+1)}(x)} = \frac{(n+1)!}{(1-x)^{n+2}}</m>.</p>

            <p>If <m>0\lt x\lt 1</m>, then <m>0\lt z\lt x</m> and <m>f^{(n+1)}(z) =\frac{(n+1)!}{(1-z)^{n+2}}\lt \frac{(n+1)!}{(1-x)^{n+2}}</m>.
              Thus
              <me>
                \abs{R_n(x)} \leq \frac{(n+1)!}{(1-x)^{n+2}}\frac{1}{(n+1)!}\abs{x^{n+1}}= \frac{(x-1)^{n+1}}{n+1}.
              </me>
            </p>

            <p>For a fixed <m>x</m>,
              <me>
                \lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{(x-1)^{n+1}}{n+1}=0,
              </me>
              hence
              <me>
                \frac{1}{1-x} = \infser[0] x^n \text{ on }  (-1,0).
              </me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
