            <p><m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\big(\sin(x) \big)  = \frac{d}{dx}\left(\infser[0] (-1)^n\frac{x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}\right)=\infser[0] (-1)^n\frac{(2n+1)x^{2n}}{(2n+1)!}=\infser[0] (-1)^n\frac{x^{2n}}{(2n)!}=\cos(x)</m>. (The summation still starts at <m>n=0</m> as there was no constant term in the expansion of <m>\sin(x)</m>).</p>
