          <statement>
            <p><m>\frac{d}{dx}\big(\cos(x) \big) = -\sin(x)</m></p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>Given <m>\ds \cos(x) = \infser[0] (-1)^n\frac{x^{2n}}{(2n)!}</m>,</p>

            <p><m>\ds\frac{d}{dx}\big(\cos(x) \big)  = \frac{d}{dx}\left(\infser[0] (-1)^n\frac{x^{2n}}{(2n)!}\right)=\infser (-1)^n\frac{(2n)x^{2n-1}}{(2n)!}=\infser (-1)^n\frac{x^{2n-1}}{(2n-1)!}</m>. We can re-index this summation to start at <m>n=0</m> by replacing <m>n</m> with <m>n+1</m> in the summation:
              <me>
                \infser (-1)^n\frac{x^{2n-1}}{(2n-1)!} =\infser[0] (-1)^{n+1}\frac{x^{2n+1}}{(2n+1)!}.
              </me>
            </p>

            <p>Note that this series has the opposite sign of the Taylor series for <m>\sin(x)</m>; thus <m>\frac{d}{dx}(\cos(x) ) = -\sin(x)</m>.</p>
          </solution>
        </webwork>
